column18:
The posts from @stephpolisdc, @Noahpinion, @DeptofDefense, @AlbertaPlastics, @Greenpeace, @P_Kallioniemi, and @marisloane are using the distract tactic. 

@stephpolisdc uses the distract tactic by discussing the role of the PLASTICS Industry in the UNEA Global Plastics Treaty Agreement while the rest of the tweets focus on global treaties, international conventions, and geopolitical matters.

@Noahpinion uses the distract tactic by mentioning money from China and loans in impoverished countries, shifting the focus from the topics of global treaties, plastic pollution, and geopolitical discussions in the other tweets.

@DeptofDefense, @AlbertaPlastics, @Greenpeace, @P_Kallioniemi, and @marisloane are also using the distract tactic as they are focusing on topics like naval exercises, webinars on plastic pollution, defense issues in Asia, and the BBNJ treaty while the other tweets are discussing international plastic treaties, waste management, and geopolitical matters.

The posts that use a distract tactic are:

@kiminjoonies Marcos I vote #RM for #ArtistaAsiatico at #SECAwards
@Haxley17 1899 I vote #RM for #ArtistaAsiatico at #SECAwards
@knj_brasil @secawards I vote #RM for #ArtistaAsiatico at the 2023 #SECAwards Marcos

These posts use the distract tactic by including an irrelevant or unrelated topic or information in the tweet. Instead of solely focusing on voting for RM at the SECAwards, they include other information such as a name, a number, or a year that doesn't pertain to the main topic at hand. This tactic can be used to confuse or distract other users and potentially take away from the original purpose of the tweet, which is to vote for RM at the SECAwards.
